19 Existing law requires a proposed guardian to file a proposed preliminary care
20 plan and budget under certain circumstances. (NRS 159A.0445) Section 5 of this
21 bill: (1) expands the circumstances under which a proposed guardian may be
22 required to file a proposed preliminary care plan and budget; and (2) requires the
23 annual review and revision of the budget under certain circumstances.
24 Existing law authorizes a court to appoint an attorney to represent a protected
25 minor or proposed protected minor in guardianship proceedings. (NRS 159A.045)
26 Section 6 of this bill provides that if a court appoints an attorney to represent a
27 protected minor or proposed protected minor in a jurisdiction where there are
28 certain established programs for legal services, the court must appoint an attorney
29 from that program in those circumstances. Section 6 also establishes provisions that
30 address the scenario under which the program for legal services has insufficient
31 funding to support the representation of each child who would otherwise qualify for
32 the appointment of an attorney under the new procedures and requires such
33 attorneys to comply with the Nevada Rules of Professional Conduct. Sections 7
34 and 10 of this bill make certain changes to reflect the procedures for the
35 appointment of an attorney under section 6.
36 Section 11 of this bill deems a protected minor or proposed protected minor
37 who is the subject of guardianship proceedings to be a party to the proceedings.
38 Existing law authorizes a court to determine that a petitioner is a vexatious
39 litigant under certain circumstances. (NRS 159A.0486) Section 12 of this bill
40 expands the circumstances under which a court may find that a petitioner is a
41 vexatious litigant to include certain acts involving a parent of a protected minor or
42 proposed protected minor.
43 Existing law authorizes a person to petition the court for the appointment of a
44 temporary guardian under certain circumstances. (NRS 159A.052, 159A.053)
45 Sections 13 and 14 make various changes to these procedures for the purpose of
46 providing that a court may require a hearing on the petition before determining the
47 need to appoint a temporary guardian.
48 Existing law requires a proposed protected minor to attend a hearing for the
49 appointment of a guardian unless certain evidence is shown to the court. (NRS
50 159A.0535) Section 15 of this bill removes this requirement related to the evidence
51 and instead authorizes the court to waive the requirement for physical attendance or
52 remote appearance for good cause shown.
53 Existing law establishes various procedures related to the issuance of orders for
54 the appointment of a guardian and the burden of proof for the petitioner and certain
55 other persons. (NRS 159A.055, 159A.0565, 159A.061) Section 16 of this bill
56 requires the petitioner to prove by clear and convincing evidence that the
57 appointment of a guardian is in the best interests of the proposed protected minor.
58 Sections 16-18 of this bill also make various changes related to the issuance of
59 such orders.
60 Existing law requires a guardian of a protected minor to perform certain duties
61 that are necessary for the proper care, maintenance, education and support of the
62 protected minor. (NRS 159A.079) Section 20 of this bill additionally requires a
63 guardian to facilitate appropriate contact between a protected minor and each parent
64 of the protected minor under certain circumstances.
65 Existing law establishes certain requirements relating to the placement of a
66 protected minor in a secured residential long-term care facility. (NRS 159A.079,
67 159A.0807) Sections 20 and 21 of this bill make these requirements applicable to
68 the placement of a protected minor in a facility that provides residential treatment.
69 Sections 20 and 22 of this bill also remove certain unnecessary references to
70 the employment of certain providers of health care by the Department of Veterans
71 Affairs.
72 Existing law requires a guardian of a protected minor to file an annual report
73 and prescribes the required contents of the report. (NRS 159A.081) Section 23 of
