74 this bill requires the report to include the frequency of visitation between the
75 protected minor and any parent of the protected minor.
76 Existing law establishes the duties of a guardian of the estate of a protected
77 minor. (NRS 159A.083) Section 24 of this bill revises and expands the duties of a
78 guardian of the estate related to investing, financial accounting, the expenditure of
79 money and the management of certain other property. Section 27 of this bill makes
80 similar changes concerning the expenditure of money related to a guardian of a
81 protected minor who is not a guardian of the estate of a protected minor. (NRS
82 159A.112) Sections 19, 25-31, 36 and 39 of this bill make various other changes
83 related to the estate of a protected minor.
84 Existing law requires a guardian to notify the court if the guardian is subject to
85 certain disqualifying events. (NRS 159A.1852) Section 32 of this bill removes
86 certain circumstances under which a guardian is required to provide such notice.
87 Existing law authorizes certain persons to petition the court to remove a
88 guardian. (NRS 159A.1853) Section 33 of this bill revises the persons who may file
89 such a petition by removing the authority of a public guardian to file the petition
90 and additionally authorizing an attorney of a protected minor or agency which
91 provides child welfare services to file the petition. Section 37 of this bill requires a
92 court to consider certain factors related to petitions filed by the parent of a
93 protected minor. (NRS 159A.1915)
94 Sections 33, 35, 38 and 40 of this bill revise the remedial actions that can be
95 taken by a court under certain circumstances.
96 Existing law authorizes a court to appoint another guardian when a guardian
97 dies or is removed by an order of the court. (NRS 159A.187) Section 34 of this bill
98 requires the court to provide notice of the matter to an agency which provides child
99 welfare services if a guardian dies or is removed and there is not a qualified
100 guardian or temporary substitute guardian willing to serve.
101 Section 1 of this bill defines the term “agency which provides child welfare
102 services” for the purposes of the provisions of law governing guardianships of
103 minors. Section 2 of this bill makes a conforming change to indicate that the
104 definition applies to the existing provisions of law.
105 Section 42 of this bill repeals various provisions of law related to the
106 guardianship of minors. Sections 2-4, 8 and 9 of this bill make conforming changes
107 relating to the repeal of such provisions.
